# <span style="color:red">My Awesome Markdown File</span>

Welcome to my markdown file! Here, I'll demonstrate some basic markdown formatting to make your documents look great.

## Table of Contents
- [Headers](#headers)
- [Emphasis](#emphasis)
- [Lists](#lists)
- [Links](#links)
- [Images](#images)
- [Code Blocks](#code-blocks)
- [Blockquotes](#blockquotes)

## Headers

You can create headers using the `#` symbol followed by a space. There are six levels of headers, with `#` representing the largest header and `######` representing the smallest header.

## Emphasis

You can make text **bold** using double asterisks or double underscores, and you can make text *italic* using single asterisks or single underscores.

## Lists

You can create ordered lists using numbers:

1. First item
2. Second item
3. Third item

You can create unordered lists using hyphens, plus signs, or asterisks:

- Item 1
- Item 2
- Item 3

## Links

You can create links using the following syntax:

[OpenAI](https://www.openai.com)

## Images

You can embed images using the following syntax:

![OpenAI Logo](https://openai.com/favicon.ico)

## Code Blocks

You can create code blocks using backticks (\`) for inline code or triple backticks (\`\`\`) for blocks of code:

```python
def greet(name):
    print("Hello, " + name + "!")